[2]
Date: Sun, 13 Apr 1997 12:40:14 +0200
Via: Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy <BSE-L@RZ.UNI-KARLSRUHE.DE>
From: "Univ.-Prof. Dr. Herbert Budka" <h.budka@akh-wien.ac.at>
Subject: CJD OR NVCJD DIAGNOSIS - USA
On Thu, 10 Apr 1997 11:21:39 -0400, Mary Fishler-Fisk <Nupensmith@aol.com>
wrote:
>Based on my own, limited, one case, but very intimate experience with CJD in
>the elderly, it seems that the medical community (at least in the US) is:
>

Thank you for this interesting personal observation. However, most of it
concerns factors which are immanent to the sociomedical system of the US
but are less likely to be seen e.g. in continental Europe.
>6) Once the clinical diagnosis of CJD is made (derived symptomatically), the
>medical community is reluctant to perform a brain biopsy because of the
>invasiveness of the procedure and its effects on the patient, but more
>importantly because of the risk of infection to the medical practitioners.
>In my mother's case, a spinal tap was done and CNS fluid sent to NIH for
>testing under their new procedure. Before the results came back, the
>hospital (Brigham and Womens in Boston - not some local community hospital
>in Paduka) discharged her without performing a biopsy, although they had
>initially been anxious to do one. Their desire to perform a biopsy
>decreased in proportion to the symptoms becoming more positive for CJD.
While I can understand your feelings, I want to point out that brain biopsy
in suspected CJD is never an easy-to-make decision, giving its invasive
character, involving some risk, and to be performed on an individual who is
not able to make decisions for himself or others. The traditional position
- not only with CJD, but also other neurodegenerative conditions as well -
is that there should be possibly treatable alternative diagnoses if a brain
biopsy is considered; otherwise it seem rather irresponsible to do it. This
traditional approach was exactly what happened in the UK when some nvCJD
cases were diagnosed by brain biopsy - in such very young people with
atypical presentations there might have been treatable alternative
diagnoses.
The problem is of course the fact that nvCJD can be diagnosed only by
tissue examination, either by biopsy or by autopsy. Given the low autopsy
rates in many countries including the US, it might be tempting to do brain
biopsies because autopsies won't be obtained - a _very cynical_ option for
me. There is no way to circumvent the need for autopsies in all suspected
TSE cases; otherwise many surveillance efforts will be futile. How about
making a legal or forensic autopsy (we call it in Austria "sanitary police
autopsy") obligatory in suspected TSEs? This is an obvious public health
problem, and many forensic autopsies are made (to my knowledge in the US by
coroners) e.g. on victims of traffic accidents - thus it shouldn't be a
problem of adequate resources. There are enough neuropathological and other
specialist laboratories in the US and elsewhere willing to diagnose
submitted cases.
I know well enough how reluctant some neurosurgeons, pathologists,
laboratory workers etc. are in working with TSE patients. With
neurosurgery, this is understandable to some degree because the whole used
instrumentarium should be discarded after the operation. With other medical
professionals, this ill-directed anxiety is much less tolerable and mostly
derives from lack of sufficient knowledge. There are enough recommendations
around how to deal safely and effectively with human TSEs. People have
become acquainted to deal with infections such as HIV which are much more
likely to be accidentally transmitted in the medical setting.
>7) The new spinal fluid test for CJD needs antemortem biopsy or post mortem
>autopsy verification. My mother's spinal fluid tested positive for CJD. No
>biopsy was performed.
A positive CSF test for the (unspecific neuronal) 14-3-3 protein supports
but does not make certain a CJD diagnosis. From my point of view, this
should not influence the decision to biopsy or not; however, most
clinicians would consider it to argue against biopsy. However, it is
desirable to expand our knowledge on the validity of the test by autopsy
control.
>8) The determination of CJD vs. nvCJD can only be made through antemortem
>biopsy or post mortem autopsy. No biopsy was performed.
Right, see above. So you correctly went for an autopsy.
>9) Upon my mother's death in a local nursing home NO ONE approached the
>family to request an autopsy. The cause of death was known (CJD) and she
was 76. The family requested an autopsy. problems for her family but > The autopsy was performed on the 20th of
February. Results are still pending.<
We have in Europe similar problems when a person dies in a nursing home and
an autopsy is desirable. That is why an obligatory legal/forensic autopsy
might be a solution.
>There were specific reasons to suspect nvCJD vs. CJD:
>
>1) Initial depression, which the family regarded as situational at the time.
>2) First physical symptom was loss of balance and blurred vision leading to
>gait ataxia.
>3) EEG atypical for CJD only two weeks before death.
>4) Course of disease from mild depression (June 1996) to death (Feb. 17,
>1997).
>5) Patient had travelled in England in the 1970's
>6) Patient was a known eater of calves brains and sweetbreads whenever they
>appeared on a restaurant menu.
All this is seen in classical CJD as well.
>Based on the foregoing,

>I believe that it will take a lot more education and public health
>intervention before CJD and nvCJD in the elderly is properly diagnosed and
>reported.
Also in Europe, it was only during the past 15 years that medical doctors
fully realized that CJD does occur in the old; our oldest patient was 84.
This is evident from the rising percentage of old CJD patients e.g. in the
UK and Austria.
>Whether or not my mother's case was CJD or nvCJD is still not known. Based
>on the symptoms and her history, I believe it was nvCJD. If we had left the
>determination entirely in the hands of the medical community, we would never
>know. More importantly, whatever scientific, medical and public health
>issues would be affected by this would have been buried with her. And, I
>believe, that is what is currently happening with most cases of CJD (whether
>CJD or nvCJD) in the elderly, at least in the US.
Maybe this issue, revolving around the need to have more autopsies, should
in the US become a topic for CJD patients' families groups?
---
